[[File:Lazica in Late Antiquity.svg|thumb|Map of Lazica and surrounding regions in [[Late Antiquity]]]]
'''Damnazes''' ({{lang-ka|დამნაზე}}; {{lang-el|Δαμνάζης}}; died 522<ref name="PLRE">{{harvnb|Martindale|Jones|Morris|1980|p=344}}.</ref>) was a 6th-century king of [[Lazica]] (western [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]]), a contemporary of the [[Sassanid Empire|Sassanid]] king of Iran [[Kavadh I]]. Damnazes, like other kings of [[Late Antiquity|Late Antique]] Lazica, are mentioned by the contemporary chronicles in the context of the rivalry between the [[Eastern Roman Empire|Eastern Roman (Byzantine) Empire]] and Sassanid Iran in the [[Caucasus]].  

Damnazes is known to the Byzantine historian [[John Malalas]]<ref>Joh. Mal. 413.</ref> as the father and predecessor of [[Tzath I of Lazica|Tzathius]], king of the Lazi. The anonymous ''[[Chronicon Paschale]]'' (''Chron. Pasch.'' s.a. 522) renders his name as ''Zamnaxes''.<ref name="PLRE"/> According to a genealogical hypothesis by Professor [[Cyril Toumanoff]], Damnazes might have been a son of the Lazic king [[Gubazes I of Lazica|Gubazes I]], who is known to have had his son as co-ruler {{circa}} 456.<ref>{{harvnb|Toumanoff|1980|pp=81–82}}.</ref>

Damnazes was a subject of the Sassanid king and, although ruling over a [[Christianity|Christian]] country, professed [[Zoroastrianism]].<ref name="Toumanoff-79">{{harvnb|Toumanoff|1980|p=79}}.</ref> On his death, his son and successor, Tzathius, rejected an Iranian coronation and repaired to [[Constantinople]] to have his accession validated by the Byzantine emperor [[Justin I]].<ref name="Toumanoff-79"/>

