{{Taxobox | image = Psilocybe medullosa (Bres.) Borovicka 713221.jpg | image_width = 234px | regnum = [[Fungi]] | divisio = [[Basidiomycota]] | classis = [[Agaricomycetes]] | ordo = [[Agaricales]] | familia = [[Strophariaceae]] | genus = [[Psilocybe]] | species = '''''P. medullosa''''' | binomial = ''Psilocybe medullosa'' | binomial_authority = ([[Bres.]]) Borovička (2007) | synonyms_ref = <ref name="urlFungorum synonymy: Psilocybe medullosa"/> | synonyms = *''Naucoria medullosa'' <small>Bres. (1898)</small> *''Galerina medullosa'' <small>(Bres.) Clémençon (1977)<ref name="Clémençon 1977"/></small> *''Phaeogalera medullosa'' <small>(Bres.) [[M.M.Moser]] (1978)<ref name="Moser 1978"/></small> }}
'''''Psilocybe medullosa''''' is a species of [[psychoactive mushroom]]. It was originally [[species description|described]] in 1898 as ''Naucoria medullosa'' by Italian mycologist [[Giacomo Bresadola]].<ref name="Bresadola 1898"/> Czech mycologist Jan Borovička transferred it to ''[[Psilocybe]]'' in 2007.<ref name="Borovička 2007"/> A widespread but rather rare species, it is found in Europe, where it grows as a [[saprobe]] on woody debris and detritus. Chemical analysis has been used to confirm the presence of the [[Psychedelic drug|psychedelic]] compounds [[psilocin]] and [[psilocybin]] in the [[basidiocarp|fruit bodies]] but probably at low levels.<ref name="Borovička 2015"/> ''Psilocybe silvatica'' is its American sister species; it differs by subtle changes in molecular markers (LSU, ITS rDNA, and others).<ref name="Borovička 2015"/>
==See also== *[[List of Psilocybe species|List of ''Psilocybe'' species]] *[[List of psilocybin mushrooms]]
